~ research_projects
The station's bulletin board displays information about ongoing research projects:

- A long-term forest dynamics study that has been tracking tree growth, mortality, and regeneration in permanent plots for over 20 years
- A seasonal bird survey documenting breeding and migratory species using the preserve
- A climate change impact study measuring phenological changes in spring flowering times
- A soil microbiome project examining the fungal and bacterial communities beneath different tree species

Each project includes contact information for the lead researcher and opportunities for student involvement. Many of the studies rely on consistent methodology continued over many years, creating valuable long-term datasets.

- Return to exploring the research station => research_station

~ field_guides
A bookshelf holds an impressive collection of well-worn field guides covering the flora and fauna of the region. These references help researchers and students accurately identify what they observe in the preserve.

The collection includes specialized guides for trees, wildflowers, ferns, mosses, lichens, birds, mammals, reptiles and amphibians, insects, and fungi. Many have notes or tabs marking locally common species.

A handwritten journal titled "Seasonal Observations" contains years of phenological records - when the first spring flowers bloom, when certain migratory birds arrive, when leaves change color in fall - potentially valuable data for tracking climate change impacts.

